docs.abstract: After recent events in Charlottesville, Va., a London exhibition by African-American artists takes on a new dimension.
docs.snippet: After recent events in Charlottesville, Va., a London exhibition by African-American artists takes on a new dimension.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — At first glance, the painting seems abstract: white shapes and streaks hovering irregularly across a night-dark background. But after a moment, the forms become clearer in this Norman Lewis painting, “America the Beautiful,” which immediately hits the eye as you enter “Soul of a Nation: Art in the Age of Black Power,” at Tate Modern. They are the peaked white hoods and flaming crosses of the Ku Klux Klan.

headline.main: A Tate Modern Show Examines Race in the U.S.
headline.print_headline: Art of the Civil Rights Era

docs.abstract: We are real people, not a bunch of demographic characteristics.
docs.snippet: We are real people, not a bunch of demographic characteristics.
docs.lead_paragraph: Sept. 16, 2017, had the potential to be an awful day on the National Mall in Washington. It started with a rally, organized by a group of Trump supporters, called the Mother of All Rallies Patriot Unification Gathering. Counterprotesters from a group called Black Lives Matter of Greater New York began shouting at the crowd. The event’s organizers shouted back, and the two sides began moving toward each other. As the situation became more combustible, onlookers recorded the scene on their phones.

docs.abstract: A movement spearheaded by a black creative director in Brooklyn is urging major retailers to commit to devoting a set amount of their shelf space to black-owned businesses.
docs.snippet: A movement spearheaded by a black creative director in Brooklyn is urging major retailers to commit to devoting a set amount of their shelf space to black-owned businesses.
docs.lead_paragraph: As protests over police brutality swept the country in recent weeks and major retailers posted messages of solidarity with black Americans on social media, Aurora James, a creative director in Brooklyn, asked herself if she actually felt that those brands were standing with her as a black woman and business owner.
